# Skeleton Component Creation Guide

This guide documents the pattern for creating skeleton loading states for components in the Aucctus application.

## Overview

Skeleton components provide visual loading placeholders that mirror the structure and layout of real components. They use a consistent shimmer animation and Aucctus design tokens to create a polished loading experience.

## Base Building Block

All skeletons use the `SkeletonBlock` component as their foundation:

[SkeletonBlock.tsx](mdc:src/app/components/Skeleton/ConceptReport/SkeletonBlock.tsx)

### Key Features of SkeletonBlock:
- Shimmer animation with 5-second ease-in-out infinite loop
- Uses `aucctus-bg-secondary-subtle` background
- Accepts `className` prop for custom sizing and shape
- Includes `aria-hidden='true'` for accessibility

## Reusable Skeleton Components

### TabViewSkeleton

For components that use TabView, use the reusable `TabViewSkeleton` component instead of creating custom tab skeletons:

[TabViewSkeleton.tsx](mdc:src/app/components/Skeleton/ConceptReport/TabViewSkeleton.tsx)

#### Key Features:
- Mirrors the exact structure of the TabView component with Tab child components
- Converts Tab button styles from SCSS to Tailwind classes
- Automatically applies proper border radius to first and last tabs
- Accepts configurable number of tabs with custom text widths
- Matches TabView's layout classes and structure
- Reusable across different skeleton components

#### Usage Example:
```typescript
import TabViewSkeleton from './TabViewSkeleton';

const MyComponentSkeleton: React.FC = () => {
  return (
    <div className='flex h-full w-full flex-col items-center self-stretch'>
      {/* Tab Navigation Skeleton - using default MarketScan-style button tabs */}
      <TabViewSkeleton
        tabs={[
          { textWidth: 'w-32' },
          { textWidth: 'w-28' },
          { textWidth: 'w-36' },
        ]}
        includeWrapper={false}
      />

      {/* Tab Content Skeleton */}
      <div className='h-full w-full items-center justify-center'>
        {/* Your content skeleton here */}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};
```

#### Props:
- `tabs`: Array of `TabSkeletonConfig` objects
  - `textWidth`: Width class for the tab label text (e.g., 'w-24', 'w-32', 'w-40')
  - Defaults to 2 tabs with medium widths if not provided
- `className`: Optional className for the outer wrapper (mirrors TabView's `className` prop, default: `''`)
- `tabGroupClassName`: Optional className for the tab group container (default: `'pointer-events-auto flex flex-1'`)
- `tabContainerClassName`: Optional className for the tab container (default: `'flex flex-1 items-center justify-center'`)
- `tabClassName`: Optional className for additional custom styling on each tab (default: `''`)
- `includeWrapper`: Whether to include the outer wrapper div (default: `true`)
  - Set to `false` if your parent component already provides the TabView wrapper structure

**Note:** The TabViewSkeleton component automatically applies the `.tabButton` styles from `tab.module.scss` converted to Tailwind classes. This includes:
- Button layout and sizing (`flex`, `justify-center`, `items-center`, `min-h-10`, `px-4`, `py-2`)
- Border styling with proper first/last child rounded corners
- Aucctus theme colors for background and borders
- Label styles matching the Tab component's `.label` class

The `tabClassName` prop is available for additional customization if needed, but the core button styles are already applied by default.

#### Style Implementation:

The TabViewSkeleton converts the `.tabButton` and `.label` SCSS styles from `tab.module.scss` to Tailwind classes:

**Tab Button (`<li>` element):**
- Base styles: `relative box-border flex h-8 min-h-10 shrink-0 cursor-pointer items-center justify-center gap-2 whitespace-nowrap px-4 py-2`
- Colors: `aucctus-bg-primary border-b border-r border-t`
- First tab: `rounded-l-lg aucctus-border-secondary border`
- Last tab: `rounded-r-lg aucctus-border-secondary border-r`

**Label (`<span>` element):**
- Typography and colors: `aucctus-text-brand-tertiary aucctus-text-sm-bold`
- Layout: `flex items-center gap-2`

#### Why Use TabViewSkeleton:
- **Consistency**: Ensures all tab skeletons match the real TabView structure
- **Maintainability**: Changes to TabView structure only require updating one component
- **Reusability**: Use across Financial Projections, Market Scan, and other tabbed interfaces
- **Accuracy**: Mirrors the exact HTML structure including `li` elements, Tab component styles, and flex classes
- **Style Parity**: Converts SCSS module styles to Tailwind for perfect visual matching

#### Real-World Examples:
- [FinancialProjectionSkeleton.tsx](mdc:src/app/components/Skeleton/ConceptReport/FinancialProjectionSkeleton.tsx) - 3 tabs with full skeleton

#### Alternative Pattern: Skeleton Labels in Real TabView

For cases where you want to use the real TabView component but with loading placeholders for the labels, you can pass SkeletonBlocks as the `label` prop:

```typescript
const marketScanTabs = useMemo(() => {
  if (showSkeletons) {
    return [
      {
        label: (
          <div className='flex items-center gap-2'>
            <SkeletonBlock className='h-4 w-4 rounded' />
            <SkeletonBlock className='h-4 w-32' />
          </div>
        ),
        value: 'trends-drivers',
      },
      {
        label: (
          <div className='flex items-center gap-2'>
            <SkeletonBlock className='h-4 w-4 rounded' />
            <SkeletonBlock className='h-4 w-24' />
          </div>
        ),
        value: 'ecosystem',
      },
    ] as TabElement[];
  }
  
  // Return normal tabs when loaded
  return normalTabs;
}, [showSkeletons]);

// Use with real TabView component
<TabView tabs={marketScanTabs} ... />
```

**When to use each pattern:**
- **TabViewSkeleton**: When showing a complete skeleton loading state for the entire tab section
- **Skeleton Labels**: When the tab structure is interactive but labels are still loading (see [MarketScanV3.tsx](mdc:src/app/pages/Concept/Report/MarketScan/v3/MarketScanV3.tsx))

## Creating a Skeleton Component

### Step 1: Analyze the Real Component Structure

Before creating a skeleton, examine the real component to understand:
- Overall layout structure (grid, flex, columns)
- Card/container backgrounds and borders
- Spacing between elements (gaps, padding, margins)
- Element sizes (headers, text, images, icons, buttons)
- Repeated patterns (lists, grids)

**Example Analysis:**

For [ExecutiveDashboard.tsx](mdc:src/app/components/ConceptOverview/ExecutiveDashboard.tsx):
- Gut check banner with title, description, and action button
- 2-column grid layout (image left, info cards right)
- Multiple card sections with icons, titles, and text
- List items with bullet points
- Carousel section with navigation

### Step 2: Mirror the Layout Structure

Recreate the exact layout structure using the same Tailwind classes from the real component:

**Real Component:**
```typescript
<div className='space-y-8'>
  <div className='aucctus-bg-secondary rounded-lg p-6'>
    {/* Gut Check Banner */}
  </div>
  <div className='grid grid-cols-1 gap-8 lg:grid-cols-2'>
    {/* Hero Section */}
  </div>
</div>
```

**Skeleton Component:**
```typescript
<div className='space-y-8'>
  <div className='aucctus-bg-secondary rounded-lg p-6'>
    {/* Gut Check Banner Skeleton */}
  </div>
  <div className='grid grid-cols-1 gap-8 lg:grid-cols-2'>
    {/* Hero Section Skeleton */}
  </div>
</div>
```

### Step 3: Replace Content with SkeletonBlocks

Replace each content element with appropriately sized `SkeletonBlock` components:

**Content Type Mappings:**

| Real Content | Skeleton Replacement |
|-------------|---------------------|
| Large header (h1, h2) | `<SkeletonBlock className='h-8 w-48' />` |
| Medium header (h3, h4) | `<SkeletonBlock className='h-6 w-32' />` |
| Small header (h5, h6) | `<SkeletonBlock className='h-5 w-24' />` |
| Body text (single line) | `<SkeletonBlock className='h-4 w-full' />` |
| Body text (partial line) | `<SkeletonBlock className='h-4 w-3/4' />` |
| Small text/label | `<SkeletonBlock className='h-3 w-24' />` |
| Icon | `<SkeletonBlock className='h-6 w-6 rounded' />` |
| Avatar/Profile Image | `<SkeletonBlock className='h-20 w-20 rounded-full' />` |
| Button | `<SkeletonBlock className='h-8 w-24 rounded' />` |
| Large image/card | `<SkeletonBlock className='h-[420px] w-full' />` |
| Badge/Tag | `<SkeletonBlock className='h-6 w-32 rounded' />` |

**Multi-line Text Pattern:**
```typescript
<div className='space-y-2'>
  <SkeletonBlock className='h-4 w-full' />
  <SkeletonBlock className='h-4 w-full' />
  <SkeletonBlock className='h-4 w-3/4' />
</div>
```

### Step 4: Handle Repeated Elements

For lists, grids, or repeated components, use `Array.from()` or `[...Array(n)]`:

**Example - List of Items:**
```typescript
<div className='space-y-3'>
  {[...Array(3)].map((_, i) => (
    <div key={i} className='flex items-center gap-3'>
      <SkeletonBlock className='h-4 w-4 rounded' />
      <SkeletonBlock className='h-4 w-full' />
    </div>
  ))}
</div>
```

**Example - Grid with Optional Count:**
```typescript
interface PESTELSkeletonProps {
  count?: number;
}

const PESTELSkeleton: React.FC<PESTELSkeletonProps> = ({ count = 3 }) => {
  return (
    <div className='grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3'>
      {Array.from({ length: count }).map((_, index) => (
        <div key={index} className='aucctus-bg-primary rounded-lg border'>
          {/* Card skeleton content */}
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
};
```

### Step 5: Preserve Visual Hierarchy

Maintain the same visual structure and hierarchy:

- Keep container backgrounds (`aucctus-bg-primary`, `aucctus-bg-secondary`)
- Preserve borders (`aucctus-border-primary`, `aucctus-border-secondary`)
- Match padding and spacing exactly
- Include shadow classes if present (`shadow-sm`, `shadow-lg`)
- Maintain border radius values

**Example - Card with Header:**
```typescript
<div className='aucctus-bg-secondary rounded-lg p-6'>
  <div className='mb-4 flex items-center gap-3'>
    <SkeletonBlock className='h-6 w-6 rounded' /> {/* Icon */}
    <SkeletonBlock className='h-6 w-32' /> {/* Title */}
  </div>
  <div className='space-y-2'>
    <SkeletonBlock className='h-4 w-full' />
    <SkeletonBlock className='h-4 w-full' />
    <SkeletonBlock className='h-4 w-2/3' />
  </div>
</div>
```

